//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: is not a collection and cannot be iterated

// `for x in v` needs `v` to be a collection. `any` is not one, even though the
// element-type projection has something to say about it: reading `#0` off a type
// walks its record leaves, and `any` has a record leaf, so the projection
// answered `any` and the loop compiled. The backend then read a scalar as a list
// header — an ASan heap-buffer-overflow, from a program with no diagnostic.
//
// A collection is a nominal record and nothing else; a type that also admits an
// i64 is not one, whatever its record leaves carry.

use std::io;

fn main() {
    let v: any = 5;
    for x in v {
        io::println("iterated");
    }
}
